Hevc format consumes almost the same file size as mp4 offered by stock camera. How? I installed this app for hevc support as reported by evaluator.
replyContent:
Hello!

Video file size can vary from scene to scene. The more motion or detail (moving people / trees) the higher the file size. It could also be the bitrate selected is higher than stock, which leads to larger files (but higher quality). If you wish for the smallest file size possible, please select the "L" quality option in Video settings :)

replyContent:
Hello,

Unfortunately the Moto X does not support the Camera2 API, which is needed for ProShot to support manual controls. Some apps have found workarounds on unsupported devices using an older API, but those are no longer supported by Google. ProShot still gives you control over exposure, white balance, and a large variety of modes and settings :)

replyContent:
Hello,

Google's API for 60fps video is very different from normal video and it doesn't support manual controls, which has made it difficult for us to add it to ProShot. We worked really hard on this app and do not advertise support for 60fps video on our store page. We hope that you consider updating your review.

content: Hi There. I'm shooting in 43:18 ultra wide but can't max out the pixels to 13mp . Although it says so when I select it, the app actually takes the photo in 7mp thus having a not so sharp image with noise. Could you help? I'm using a Nexus 6. Thanks.  Otherwise great app.
replyContent:
Hello,

Your camera's image sensor has a native aspect ratio of 4:3. replyContent:
Hello,

Timelapse should be functioning normally, but if you're having trouble, here are a few things to try:
1) Increase the length of the interval to 2s
2) Reduce the image resolution
3) Turn off the histogram
4) Don't save to the SD card
5) Clear your cache, uninstall ProShot, restart your device, reinstall

Best Regards,
Eddie
